            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#GC">
                <p>Near these doorposts to the temple of Sarapis, Karneades of Barke, the temple-warden, son of Eukritos, dedicated this sacred altar to Hestia, visitor, together with his wife Pythia and his daughter Erasos. In exchange, you reigning over Zeus' magnificent house, that they may always have well-pleasing happiness of life.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--68 cm high, 42 cm wide, 34 cm deep. Letters 2cm high. Six lines of verse, regarding dedication to Serapis and Isis. Amphi parastasi taisde Sarapidos Hestiai hagnon bomon Barkaios Karneades etheto, Eukritou huios, xeine, ho neokoros ha th'homolektros Puthias ha keinou kai thugater Eraso, anth'hon, o krainousa Dios megalaucheas oikous, thumaren biotas olbon echoien aei'. Part of an altar, dedicated by neokoros ('temple warden') Karneades of Barke (city of Cyrenaica), son of Eukritos, together with his wife and daughter. Set up at one side of the entrance to the temple of Serapis. Poss. that the dedicant actually an 'imported' Egyptian involved in the setting up of the cult, even a priest? cf. CIL 10.6989 = ILLPa 49--></p>
            </div>
